7 participants worth of data. They were recruited through SONA or were RAs. 120 items per participant, encountered in lists of 12 items. With three conditions (binocular, cfs, not-studied), there were four items in each condition in each list. Of those four items, three were encountered in a â€œgoâ€ test trial, and one was in a â€œno-goâ€ test trial. So, 1/4 of test-trials were no-go. This leaves up to 30 items in go trials per condition, per participant.

New in this version of the experiment

  • During naming trial, participants were cued with two apertures instead of one. These two aperatures were the same two that participants would have encounterd in Masterâ€™s experiment 1, during the 2AFC. Specifically, these are the matching parts that participants would be trying to select.

  • The object emerging from noise in the go/no-go test trials had 2 bullet-holes removed from the whole (instead of two), one in the place of each aperature.

Previous updates

  • Binocular objects were studied for up to 5 seconds (rather than up to 4 seconds)

  • All objects that were studied (CFS or Binocular) reached 100% opacity after 2.5 seconds

  • The above point means that there was no variability / calibration of opacity to each participant

The primary goal of these modification was in improve naming performance for items that were studied binocularly. However, there was a bug in the code when labelling the condition of the items. So, these modifications was not necessary as Naming performance was already okay for binocularly studied objects.
